Read in the shapefile

## Read in shapefile using sf
ak_regions <- read_sf("shapefiles/ak_regions_simp.shp")

#this creates a plot for each column in dataframe (region_id, region, and mgmt_area)
plot(ak_regions)

Notice on the plot there’s some weird plotting to the right It’s splitting over 180o, so plots the western most Alutians to the right/ We need to define a coordinate reference system (crs) There is a very nice package crsuggestthat can help you choosing the right projection for your data.

Change the projection

These data are in WGS_1984 (#4326). We’re going to transform them to Alaska Albers (EPSG code = 3338).

ak_regions_3338 <- ak_regions %>%
  st_transform(crs = 3338)

#Check the reference system
st_crs(ak_regions_3338)

Notice that the population file doesn’t give us the region name. We need to figure out which region each city is in Lots of ways to join in the st package (left, where lines cross, etc)

But first we need to coerce the pop dataframe into a sf type Give it the columns that are coordinates and the datum the data are. (Not what you want them to be! We are assuming 4326; be good with your metadata!). The remove=F ensures that when we create the geometry column (spatial column) we can retain the original lat and long columns

pop_4326 <- st_as_sf(pop, 
                  coords = c('lng', 'lat'),
                  crs = 4326,
                  remove = F)

Now our population file is in datum 4326, but the mapping files are in 3338 We need to make them the same

pop_3338 <- pop_4326 %>% 
  st_transform(crs=3338)

Summarize the data

We can drop the geometry on the population file now (it’s sticky and will stick around unless we tell it to drop it) Here we will make it unsticky (will drop when we summarize the data)

pop_region <- pop_joined %>% 
  as.data.frame()
names(pop_region)
## [1] "year"       "city"       "lat"        "lng"        "population"
## [6] "region_id"  "region"     "mgmt_area"  "geometry"

Now let’s join them

pop_region <- pop_joined %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  summarise(total_pop = sum(population))

head(pop_region)

Now we need to join the population information with our region boundary information. Note that now we have a 4th map (total_pop)

pop_region_3338 <- left_join(ak_regions_3338, pop_region, by = "region")
plot(pop_region_3338)

You can group by and summarize by sf objects as well dataframe For example, management areas. Let’s calcualte population by mgmt area

pop_mgmt_3338 <- pop_region_3338 %>% 
  group_by(mgmt_area) %>% 
  summarize(total_pop = sum(total_pop))

plot(pop_mgmt_3338)

There are special sf arguements for dplyr. For example, adding the do_union command gets rid of the little gaps due to low resolution maps being grouped

pop_mgmt_3338 <- pop_region_3338 %>% 
  group_by(mgmt_area) %>% 
  summarize(total_pop = sum(total_pop), do_union=FALSE)

plot(pop_mgmt_3338)

Making maps

Can use ggplot -it’s now integrated with sf objects Note that order is backwards, so include the arguments mapping. To make the legend a gradiant use the scale_fill_contiuous command.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data= pop_mgmt_3338, mapping=aes(fill = total_pop)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(fill = "Total Population") +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "khaki", high =  "firebrick", labels = comma)

# Using base maps to plot our points (like your sites) Working with another projection, cuz base data uses it and we’re stuck with it

pop_3857 <- pop_3338 %>%
  st_transform(crs = 3857)

Get base map using a function from the ggplot server using a bounding box The tile servers have some issues with bounding box datums So you need to run this solution (based on solution found on githup) Run it on the ggmap object (tiles back from the server)

# Define a function to fix the bbox to be in EPSG:3857
# See https://github.com/dkahle/ggmap/issues/160#issuecomment-397055208
ggmap_bbox_to_3857 <- function(map) {
  if (!inherits(map, "ggmap")) stop("map must be a ggmap object")
  # Extract the bounding box (in lat/lon) from the ggmap to a numeric vector, 
  # and set the names to what sf::st_bbox expects:
  map_bbox <- setNames(unlist(attr(map, "bb")), 
                       c("ymin", "xmin", "ymax", "xmax"))
  
  # Coonvert the bbox to an sf polygon, transform it to 3857, 
  # and convert back to a bbox (convoluted, but it works)
  bbox_3857 <- st_bbox(st_transform(st_as_sfc(st_bbox(map_bbox, crs = 4326)), 3857))
  
  # Overwrite the bbox of the ggmap object with the transformed coordinates 
  attr(map, "bb")$ll.lat <- bbox_3857["ymin"]
  attr(map, "bb")$ll.lon <- bbox_3857["xmin"]
  attr(map, "bb")$ur.lat <- bbox_3857["ymax"]
  attr(map, "bb")$ur.lon <- bbox_3857["xmax"]
  map
}

Get bounding box Start by guessing the zoom level (may need to play with this) Run the fixing function from above

bbox <- c(-170, 52, -130, 64)   # This is roughly southern Alaska
ak_map <- get_stamenmap(bbox, zoom = 4)
## Source : http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/4/0/4.png
## Source : http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/4/1/4.png
## Source : http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/4/2/4.png
## Source : http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/4/0/5.png
## Source : http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/4/1/5.png
## Source : http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/4/2/5.png
ak_map_3857 <- ggmap_bbox_to_3857(ak_map)

Map the population data Need background aes stuff to not run, so set inherit.aes = F Set scale color for legend

ggmap(ak_map_3857) + 
  geom_sf(data = pop_3857, aes(color = population), inherit.aes = F) +
